%S A389241 0,1,3,6,9,13,19,25,32,39,47,56,66,77,89,100
%N A389241 Maximum number of distinct consecutive sums of a permutation of [n].
%C A389241 Erdős asked whether this sequence is o(n^2), motivated by A234813.
%C A389241 Konieczny proved the answer is "no", both by constructing an explicit permutation with n^2/4 distinct consecutive sums, and also showing that a random permutation has ~n^2(1+e^-2)/4 distinct consecutive sums.
%D A389241 P. Erdős, Problems in number theory and combinatorics. Proceedings of the Sixth Manitoba Conference on Numerical Mathematics (Univ. Manitoba, Winnipeg, Man., 1976) (1977), 35-58.
%D A389241 P. Erdős, Problems and results on combinatorial number theory. III. Number theory day (Proc. Conf., Rockefeller Univ., New York, 1976) (1977), 43-72.
%D A389241 P. Erdős and R. Graham, Old and new problems and results in combinatorial number theory. Monographies de L'Enseignement Mathématique (1980).
%H A389241 Thomas Bloom, <a href="https://www.erdosproblems.com/34">Problem 34</a>, Erdős Problems.
%H A389241 Erdős problems database contributors, <a href="https://github.com/teorth/erdosproblems/issues/95">Issue #95</a> linking Erdős problems to the OEIS.
%H A389241 J. Konieczny, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1504.07156">On consecutive sums in permutations</a>. arXiv:1504.07156 [math.CO], 2015-2021.
%e A389241 For n=5, {1, 2, 3, 5, 4} is one of many having 13 distinct consecutive sums, namely 1, 2, 3=1+2, 4, 5=2+3, 1+2+3, 3+5, 5+4, 2+3+5, 1+2+3+5, 3+5+4, 2+3+5+4, and 1+2+3+5+4.
%e A389241 For n=8, {1, 3, 8, 4, 6, 7, 2, 5} and its reversal are the unique permutations that have 32 distinct consecutive sums.
%o A389241 (Python)
%o A389241 from itertools import combinations, permutations
%o A389241 def f(p): return len(set(sum(p[i:j]) for i, j in combinations(range(len(p)+1),2)))
%o A389241 def a(n): return max(f(p) for p in permutations(range(1, n+1)))
%o A389241 print([a(n) for n in range(10)]) # _Michael S. Branicky_, Oct 07 2025
